{{Orphan|date=February 2009}}
'''Net Authority''' was a [[parody]] web site created in 2001 by Rudis Muiznieks<ref>{{citation|author=netcraft.com|url=http://toolbar.netcraft.com/site_report?url=http://www.netauthority.org |title=Netcraft site report for www.netauthority.org|date=January 25, 2008}}</ref> that pretended to be a [[Christian]] [[Internet censorship]] site for recording and tracking other web sites containing offensive content. The site shut down shortly afterwards, when Muiznieks found that it had gotten completely out of hand. After receiving a legal threat, he closed it down on the recommendation of his employer.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://codeword.xyz/2017/03/15/that-time-i-trolled-the-entire-internet/ | title=That Time I Trolled the Entire Internet | author=Rudis Muiznieks | date=2017-03-15 | publisher=Rudis Muiznieks (codeword.xyz)}}</ref>
He reopened it a few years later in a watered-down form. It finally ceased operations in February 2008, allegedly because "fundamentalist religion [was] doing such a fantastic job of parodying itself" that Net Authority "could only pale in comparison to the real thing".<ref>{{citation|first=Rudis|last=Muiznieks|title=Net Authority|date=February 3, 2008|url=http://www.netauthority.org/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080223132339/http://www.netauthority.org/index.html|archivedate=February 23, 2008}}</ref>
Net Authority purported to encourage an "Internet Acceptable Use Policy" to prohibit sites containing [[pornographic]], [[hatred|hateful]] or [[blasphemous]] material, and sites containing "[[bestiality]], including [[Miscegenation|interracial]] relationships". Users could easily submit websites themselves, which would then be added to the database.
Notable victims included the BBC Radio 4's ''[[The Now Show]]'' in 2007<ref>{{citation|last=Punt|first=Steve |last2=Dennis|first2=Hugh|title=The Now Show|periodical=BBC Radio 4|date=13 July 2007}}</ref> and ''[[The Register]]'' in 2001,<ref>{{citation|first=Lester|last=Haines|title=Reg faces blasphemy charge: Praise the Lord or face the consequences|periodical=The Register|date=June 21, 2001|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2001/06/21/reg_faces_blasphemy_charge/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071114033915/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2001/06/21/reg_faces_blasphemy_charge/|archivedate=November 14, 2007|deadurl=no}}</ref> who "f[e]ll for it completely".<ref>{{citation|first=Lester|last=Haines|title=Reg victim of blasphemy hoax|periodical=The Register|date=June 21, 2001|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2001/06/21/reg_victim_of_blasphemy_hoax/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070811005136/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2001/06/21/reg_victim_of_blasphemy_hoax/|archivedate=August 11, 2007|deadurl=no}}.</ref>
