{{Infobox religious building | building_name =Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet | infobox_width = | image =3-4view Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet Paris.jpg | image_size = | caption =Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet: Façade of the church | map_type = | map_size = | map_caption = | location =23, Rue des Bernardins, 75005 Paris, France | geo = {{coord|48.849167|2.350278|display=inline,title}} | religious_affiliation =[[Roman Catholic]] | rite = [[Tridentine Mass]] | region = [[Île-de-France (region)|Île-de-France]] | state = | province =[[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Paris|Archdiocese of Paris]], since 1977 used by [[Traditionalist Catholic|traditionalist]] [[Society of St. Pius X]] | territory = | prefecture = | sector = | district = | cercle = | municipality = | consecration_year = | status = | functional_status = Active | heritage_designation = | leadership = [Patrick de La Rocque]] (since 2014) | website ={{url|http://www.saintnicolasduchardonnet.fr}} | architecture =yes | architect = | architecture_type =Church | architecture_style =[[Classical architecture|Classical]] | general_contractor = | facade_direction = | groundbreaking ={{start date|1658}} | year_completed ={{end date|1703}} | construction_cost = | specifications =yes | capacity = | length = | width = | width_nave = | height_max = | dome_quantity = | dome_height_outer = | dome_height_inner = | dome_dia_outer = | dome_dia_inner = | minaret_quantity = | minaret_height = | spire_quantity = | spire_height = | materials = | nrhp = | added = | refnum = }}
'''Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet''' is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[Church (building)|church]] in the centre of Paris, France, located in the [[5th arrondissement, Paris|5th arrondissement]].<ref>{{Structurae|id=s0021865|title=Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet Church}}</ref> Since 1977, after expelling the parish priest and his assistants the church has been used by [[Traditionalist Catholic|traditionalist]] [[Society of St. Pius X]] and remains in the Society's hands.
==History until 1977== [[File:Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet Nave, Paris, France - Diliff.jpg|thumb|left|The nave]] {{Expand section|date=March 2009}}
The church was first built in the 13th century and was reconstructed between 1656 and 1763.
In 1612, Adrien Bourdoise founded a seminary at Saint-Nicolas.
In the late 17th century noted [[harpsichord]]ist [[Jean-Nicolas Geoffroy]] (1633–1694) served as titular organist of the church.
In the 19th century the adjacent Mutualité site was occupied by a seminary. There, [[Ernest Renan]] studied under the direction of the [[Abbé Dupanloup]], who attained celebrity in 1838 when he reconciled the notoriously amoral diplomat [[Talleyrand]], who had received the minor orders at Saint-Nicholas, to the church on his death-bed. (Dupanloup subsequently became [[Bishop of Orléans]] and a member of the ''[[Académie française]]'').
Since 1905, the city of Paris, following the [[1905 French law on the separation of Church and State|law on the separation of Church and State]], claims ownership of the church but grants the Roman Catholic Church a free usage right.
==1977 occupation and consequences== {{confusing|section|date=August 2017}} In 1977, eleven years before the [[Ecône consecrations]], members of the Society of St. Pius X led by [[François Ducaud-Bourget]] expelled the parish priest and his assistants and occupied the church.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sspx.org/en/25-years-of-the-sspx-fr-angles-talk-part-2 |title=25 years of the SSPX: part 2 |website=Society of Saint Pius X |access-date=2016-11-20}}</ref>
Shortly afterwards, the city of Paris gave an eviction order. In 1978, the [[Court of Cassation (France)|Court of Cassation]] confirmed that the occupation was illegal but the order of eviction was never implemented.<ref name="v1">[http://www.v1.paris.fr/BMO/delib/CMDELIB20020624/CMDELIB200206242002_V._83.htm 2002 V. 83 - Vœu relatif à l'occupation de l'église Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311042006/http://www.v1.paris.fr/BMO/delib/CMDELIB20020624/CMDELIB200206242002_V._83.htm |date=2007-03-11 }}</ref> On 20 February 1987, the ''[[Council of State (France)|Conseil d'État]]'' ruled that the disturbance to [[public order]] resulting from an expulsion would be higher than that resulting from the illegal occupation.<ref>[http://www.v1.paris.fr/BMO/debat/cmdebat20020624/CMDEBAT20020624-183.htm 183 - Vœu présenté par M. Sylvain GAREL et les membres du groupe "Les Verts" sur l'occupation de l'église Saint-Nicolas-du-Chardonnet]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{fr icon}}</ref>
In 1993, the SSPX members, led by [[Philippe Laguérie]], unsuccessfully attempted to occupy another church in Paris, [[St-Germain l'Auxerrois]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120207021112/http://v.i.v.free.fr/msd/nv-lefebvre-09-09-2004.html Les Lebevristes se déchirent], ''[[La Croix]]'', 9 September 2004. (Archived: 7 February 2012) {{fr icon}}</ref>
On 22 June 2002, the municipal council of Paris passed a resolution that the Society of St Pius X should be expelled from the church,<ref name="v1"/> against the wishes of the [[French Socialist Party|socialist]] Mayor [[Bertrand Delanoë]],<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110927053839/http://lesverts.fr/article.php3?id_article=1077 Saint Nicolas du Chardonnet: Un procès à la hauteur de nos espérances], ''[[The Greens (France)|Les Verts]]''. (Archived: 27 September 2011) {{fr icon}}</ref> who considered it an internal matter of the Catholic Church, remarking that the [[Archbishop of Paris]] had not requested that the Society be expelled.{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}
==Current situation== It is now the Society's first church in the city of Paris itself, the second being [[Bazar de la Charité#Chapel of Our Lady of Consolation|Notre-Dame-de-Consolation Chapel]]<ref>[http://laportelatine.org/district/prieure/SteGermaine/horaires_offices/nd_de_consolation_horaires_offices_2013_2014.php Chapelle Notre-Dame de Consolation : horaires des offices pour l'année 2013-2014]</ref> (others exist in the [[Île de France]]) and although it is not their official French headquarters<ref>The SSPX list their French headquarters as ''Prieure Saint Pie X, 11, rue Cluseret, BP 125'', from [http://www.sspx.org/headquarters.html Headquarters of the SSPX] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060811210614/http://www.sspx.org/headquarters.html |date=2006-08-11 }}, from their website in the USA</ref> it is seen as their de facto national centre.{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}
On Sundays, Mass is celebrated in the church at 08.00, 09.00, and 10.30, 12.15 and 18.30 .<ref>Fraternité Sacerdotale Saint-Pie X, [http://www.laportelatine.org/district/lieux/page.php?no_dept=75 "La Porte Latine"].</ref>
